00:01:04.030 --> 00:01:10.240
At the end of this, you'll be
able to sketch a basic value

00:01:10.240 --> 00:01:15.370
stream map, demonstrate some
basic analysis of those maps,

00:01:15.370 --> 00:01:20.380
and then recognize some steps
for process improvement using

00:01:20.380 --> 00:01:22.450
your value stream map.

00:01:22.450 --> 00:01:25.080
You recognize this?

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:27.810
Back to the hot dog stand.

00:01:27.810 --> 00:01:33.720
And it may not look exactly
like the ones you made.

00:01:33.720 --> 00:01:36.840
So, starts with
taking the order,

00:01:36.840 --> 00:01:39.480
placing it in the "in" tray.

00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:42.060
Get the order, cook the
dogs, put them in the bun,

00:01:42.060 --> 00:01:43.800
and wrap them at the fruit.

00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:46.650
And then it's a
question of, do they

00:01:46.650 --> 00:01:48.120
need another hot dog or not?

00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:50.610
If they don't, they will
go up to the order out,

00:01:50.610 --> 00:01:53.910
if they do then you go over.

00:01:53.910 --> 00:01:56.100
Check if the order is OK.

00:01:56.100 --> 00:01:58.080
At the beverage delivered
to the customer,

00:01:58.080 --> 00:02:01.710
and the customer leaves
with their hot dogs.

00:02:01.710 --> 00:02:07.440
So, value, as we think
about it in Lean,

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:12.270
is really value
for the customer.

00:02:12.270 --> 00:02:14.220
it's not value for us.

00:02:14.220 --> 00:02:17.295
And in particular
in health care,

00:02:17.295 --> 00:02:19.890
we know so much about
the engineering side.

00:02:19.890 --> 00:02:23.220
But in health care we really
have a difficult time coming

00:02:23.220 --> 00:02:24.060
to terms with this.

00:02:24.060 --> 00:02:27.270
We struggle with it, because
it is oftentimes about,

00:02:27.270 --> 00:02:31.020
how do things work best
for us, and not so much,

00:02:31.020 --> 00:02:33.675
how do things work
best for the patients?

00:02:36.210 --> 00:02:37.950
If it was the other
way, we probably

00:02:37.950 --> 00:02:39.478
wouldn't have waiting rooms.

00:02:39.478 --> 00:02:40.520
We do have waiting rooms.

00:02:40.520 --> 00:02:43.200
We have waiting rooms all over.

00:02:43.200 --> 00:02:47.610
In fact, I work in the
Emergency Department over at BI,

00:02:47.610 --> 00:02:51.060
and we have recently
decided that we're

00:02:51.060 --> 00:02:53.100
going to make it
a formal process

00:02:53.100 --> 00:02:55.560
to open our waiting room.

00:02:55.560 --> 00:02:57.720
Because we don't really
want it, and it's

00:02:57.720 --> 00:03:00.000
going to be paged out
as a formal process,

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.540
as a formal step, that
now we decide we open it,

00:03:03.540 --> 00:03:05.190
and we will not
have it open if we

00:03:05.190 --> 00:03:07.620
have any open beds
in the Department,

00:03:07.620 --> 00:03:09.660
because it doesn't
make any sense.

00:03:09.660 --> 00:03:13.920
Anyway, that would be
value for the customer.

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:16.470
Identify the value
stream, map out

00:03:16.470 --> 00:03:21.810
the end to end linkages between
the processes, what goes on.

00:03:21.810 --> 00:03:24.060
Then we focus on
making flow continuous

00:03:24.060 --> 00:03:27.690
from one end to the other.

00:03:27.690 --> 00:03:30.570
Pull, that we heard
about earlier on.

00:03:30.570 --> 00:03:32.820
Let the customer
pull the value rather

00:03:32.820 --> 00:03:36.600
than us producing a whole bunch
of things that then get piled

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:39.510
up and some of it gets wasted.

00:03:39.510 --> 00:03:41.850
Then we do it over
and over again,

00:03:41.850 --> 00:03:45.480
because we're never really
going to reach perfection.

00:03:45.480 --> 00:03:49.380
But we're going to strive
for the perfection.

00:03:49.380 --> 00:03:54.640
So value stream mapping, it's a
tool to improve our processes,

00:03:54.640 --> 00:03:57.660
our whole production,
by identifying

00:03:57.660 --> 00:03:59.610
steps that add value.

00:03:59.610 --> 00:04:04.290
And also by identifying
waste in our processes.

00:04:04.290 --> 00:04:06.990
We follow the value
creation process,

00:04:06.990 --> 00:04:09.630
we talked about, from
one end to the other.

00:04:09.630 --> 00:04:11.760
And you need to go
to Gemba to get out

00:04:11.760 --> 00:04:14.040
there and see what happens.

00:04:14.040 --> 00:04:16.200
You can't sit in an office--

00:04:16.200 --> 00:04:17.790
you can sit in an
office and you can

00:04:17.790 --> 00:04:22.210
think that you know what
is actually happening.

00:04:22.210 --> 00:04:24.840
But in reality you don't.

00:04:24.840 --> 00:04:26.550
I have some examples,
I'll get to that

00:04:26.550 --> 00:04:30.840
a little later, from our final
hospital, if we have the time.

00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:34.620
But when you go and look at
what actually takes place,

00:04:34.620 --> 00:04:37.890
you get surprised,
even in the environment

00:04:37.890 --> 00:04:41.000
that you work in yourself.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:43.370
Because we all think that
we have the solutions

00:04:43.370 --> 00:04:47.510
to the problems that we
encounter, and sometimes we do,

00:04:47.510 --> 00:04:49.490
and sometimes we actually don't.

00:04:49.490 --> 00:04:53.630
The value stream map is the
process maps that we've done.

00:04:53.630 --> 00:04:56.540
Some of you have
already added your data.

00:04:56.540 --> 00:05:01.820
It can be time data, it can
be quality data, inventory,

00:05:01.820 --> 00:05:05.900
resources, people,
things, and whatever else.

00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:09.080
But don't clot your
maps with things that

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:11.160
are not really useful for you.

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:15.080
So there are some steps to
creating these values to be

00:05:15.080 --> 00:05:21.560
maps, and the first is to
define customer value, and then

00:05:21.560 --> 00:05:22.700
the process.

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:27.155
And we can discuss
what customer value is.

00:05:27.155 --> 00:05:29.630
That is a debate you can
see among yourselves here

00:05:29.630 --> 00:05:31.430
with the maps that
you've created.

00:05:31.430 --> 00:05:34.100
You did not all
agree on what adds

00:05:34.100 --> 00:05:36.530
value, what
customers potentially

00:05:36.530 --> 00:05:38.660
would be willing to pay for.

00:05:38.660 --> 00:05:39.360
An example.

00:05:39.360 --> 00:05:45.170
We've just done a Lean project
with our registration people.

00:05:45.170 --> 00:05:47.610
Patients need to be
registered, right?

00:05:47.610 --> 00:05:51.860
And is that a value
added process?

00:05:51.860 --> 00:05:53.660
We weren't quite
agreeing on that,

00:05:53.660 --> 00:05:57.290
at least not initially, because
you can say, well, I mean,

00:05:57.290 --> 00:05:59.180
patients, they don't care.

00:05:59.180 --> 00:06:00.950
But in fact, if you
dig a little deeper

00:06:00.950 --> 00:06:03.770
they probably do, because
if you aren't registered,

00:06:03.770 --> 00:06:05.720
your visit is not
linked to your record,

00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:07.460
and then it's not
part of your history.

00:06:07.460 --> 00:06:10.920
And then it's hard to
tie everything together.

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:13.250
So identify the value
added and the waste

00:06:13.250 --> 00:06:14.870
steps is the next one.

00:06:14.870 --> 00:06:17.180
And then, in order
to change things

00:06:17.180 --> 00:06:18.890
for the better in
the future, you

00:06:18.890 --> 00:06:21.530
need to understand what
you're currently doing.

00:06:21.530 --> 00:06:23.960
So you do a map of
the current state.

00:06:23.960 --> 00:06:26.420
Where are we now?

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:31.400
And then you analyze that map
and you find opportunities

00:06:31.400 --> 00:06:33.590
for improving things.

00:06:33.590 --> 00:06:39.110
You can look at bottlenecks,
you can look at work load

00:06:39.110 --> 00:06:42.920
balancing, and you can have
that as an open discussion

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:45.020
of what can you make better.

00:06:45.020 --> 00:06:50.047
And now you've just heard
the module on people.

00:06:50.047 --> 00:06:51.380
And that's actually interesting.

00:06:51.380 --> 00:06:55.950
If you involve everybody
in this process,

00:06:55.950 --> 00:06:58.400
you can get a lot of
good synergy in it.

00:06:58.400 --> 00:07:01.940
And by involving
some of the skeptics

00:07:01.940 --> 00:07:03.830
you can actually win
them over sometimes.

00:07:03.830 --> 00:07:06.080
We've done that too,
surprisingly enough.

00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:08.540
But it is possible.

00:07:08.540 --> 00:07:11.180
Then you use that to create
your future state map,

00:07:11.180 --> 00:07:12.890
and then you make an
action plan for how

00:07:12.890 --> 00:07:14.400
you are going to get there.

00:07:14.400 --> 00:07:20.520
And I think we'll get to that on
day three, in the A3 thinking.

00:07:20.520 --> 00:07:26.040
All right, we're back to this
one that follows the value

00:07:26.040 --> 00:07:27.450
creation process.

00:07:27.450 --> 00:07:30.920
And you have, in
your groups, assessed

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:35.390
the values and the wastes
for each of the processes.

00:07:35.390 --> 00:07:39.140
And now it's time
to add some data.

00:07:39.140 --> 00:07:42.590
I think that we'll
just go with the map

00:07:42.590 --> 00:07:46.700
that you had handed out, all
the data should be on it.

00:07:46.700 --> 00:07:49.820
Time's in seconds, and there's
some quality measurements

00:07:49.820 --> 00:07:53.245
as well, because
the processes there

00:07:53.245 --> 00:07:55.120
weren't perfect the
whole way through, right?

00:07:55.120 --> 00:07:57.260
It was 100% every time.

00:07:57.260 --> 00:08:00.410
We know our demand, our
current demand at least,

00:08:00.410 --> 00:08:02.790
for the 50 customers.

00:08:02.790 --> 00:08:04.860
And we know how long
we're open, so we

00:08:04.860 --> 00:08:10.350
know how long time we have to
fulfill the orders as they are.

00:08:10.350 --> 00:08:13.770
The takt time is
our available times.

00:08:13.770 --> 00:08:18.180
It's 4 hours time 60 minutes,
that should be 240 minutes.

00:08:18.180 --> 00:08:21.370
And the demand is 50 customers.

00:08:21.370 --> 00:08:26.430
So we have 4.8, or 288
seconds per customer.

00:08:26.430 --> 00:08:31.680
We also know that the cycle
time from what we added up

00:08:31.680 --> 00:08:36.159
is actually 446 seconds.

00:08:36.159 --> 00:08:39.030
So we can all understand that
they're pretty stressed, right,

00:08:39.030 --> 00:08:43.169
because they're spending more
time than they really have.

00:08:43.169 --> 00:08:45.330
And then there's the
alternative calculation

00:08:45.330 --> 00:08:51.030
where you've taken the set out
and the clean out time out.

00:08:51.030 --> 00:08:53.520
Some of you might have
been thinking about that

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:55.500
and done that when
things are slow.

00:08:55.500 --> 00:08:59.130
And that gives you a
little shorter takt time.

00:08:59.130 --> 00:09:01.590
But there's still an imbalance
between the takt time

00:09:01.590 --> 00:09:02.430
and the cycle time.

00:09:02.430 --> 00:09:05.270
So you're still in the negative.

00:09:05.270 --> 00:09:06.940
But you have two workers.

00:09:06.940 --> 00:09:11.330
So the question is, can
you meet their demands?

00:09:11.330 --> 00:09:12.080
All right.

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:15.410
If you take the second
handout that you

00:09:15.410 --> 00:09:19.460
got, with the
different processes on,

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:20.960
write down in your groups.

00:09:20.960 --> 00:09:23.900
You have 10 minutes, you'll
get a warning after 7.

00:09:23.900 --> 00:09:28.610
Write down who is doing what,
how much time they're spending,

00:09:28.610 --> 00:09:32.270
and then as well whether it's
value added or non value added.

00:09:35.313 --> 00:09:36.980
All right, we're going
to start off here

00:09:36.980 --> 00:09:38.720
because you look very ready.

00:09:38.720 --> 00:09:42.070
You're starting to search
for solutions, here.

